Narrative: At approximately 3:57 PM CDT on April [XXX], an Aurora truck was traveling northbound on [XXX] in autonomy north of Centerville, TX. The Aurora truck encountered shreds of tire in the roadway. The left lane was blocked by another truck and not clear for the Aurora truck to merge away from the tire shreds. Per the company's protocol and when there is a vehicle operator providing supervision, the vehicle operator elected to disengage autonomy to navigate through the tire shreds. The vehicle operator pulled over to the shoulder to inspect the truck and found a torn air hose causing the air tanks to lose pressure. The vehicle operator drove to a nearby truck stop to enable the repair work to be completed. No injuries were reported.

An unoccupied Zoox vehicle in autonomous mode was traveling south on [XXX], slowing and preparing to make a right turn onto [XXX] in San Francisco. At that time, an approaching e-scooterist was also traveling south on [XXX] in the curb lane offset from the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle braked to a stop as the e-scooterist was beginning to enter the intersection. The e-scooterist then made contact with the right rear side of the stopped Zoox vehicle, and the e-scooterist fell to the ground next to the Zoox vehicle. The Zoox vehicle then started to move and completed the right turn onto [XXX], coming to a stop a short distance down [XXX]. The e-scooterist then walked themself and the e-scooter over to the sidewalk, where they were met by a member of the Zoox operations team, and they reported "[REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION] chipped tooth and jaw pain." The e-scooterist declined medical attention and rode their e-scooter from the scene after exchanging information. There was no damage to the Zoox vehicle and the police were not called.

On May [XXX], 2025, a Plus autonomous test truck was driving in autonomous mode on a public highway in Texas with a Safety Driver.  Plus's safety drivers are experienced and well-trained. The Safety Driver operating the particular vehicle has 12-years of over-the-road commercial vehicle driving experience. All safety drivers are trained to manage potential hazards they may encounter on the roads and are encouraged to retake control of the vehicle whenever necessary to ensure safe operation.  
Here, the Plus vehicle was traveling Northbound on [XXX] at approximately 63 mph in mild to moderate traffic with clear weather conditions.  According to the video camera log, the truck was in autonomous mode when a black SUV traveling in the right-most driving lane swerved to the right into the emergency lane (i.e., the shoulder) to avoid a vehicle that had stopped before it in the driving lane. Seeing the disabled vehicle in the driving lane, the Plus Safety Driver took control of the truck by applying the brakes and began to decelerate the vehicle. Two vehicles traveling behind the black SUV in the same lane then swerved to the left and into the lane in which the Plus vehicle was traveling.  The left side of the second of these vehicles (a minivan) made contact with the Plus truck's right side. [REDACTED, MAY CONTAIN CONFIDENTIAL BUSINESS INFORMATION]
The Plus truck swerved slightly into the lane to its left as a result of the contact, avoiding a pickup truck that was passing by it. The Safety Driver then re-centered the vehicle into the truck's original lane. After the contact, the minivan moved into the rightmost lane and then ultimately came to a stop in the emergency lane.  The Plus Safety Driver changed lanes and also brought the truck to a stop in the emergency lane.
A Police report was taken at the scene, but the Plus Safety Driver did not receive a copy of it.  Based on our best information, none of the passengers in the minivan reported injuries and the only damage was to the vehicle's driver-side tire.  The minivan nevertheless was towed away from the scene.  The Plus truck did not have any damage and was able to continue driving to its destination.

Narrative: A Zoox vehicle in autonomy was stopped at a stop sign on southbound [XXX] at [XXX] waiting for a crossing vehicle to clear the intersection, when it was rear-ended by an e-scooter rider. The e-scooter rider initially passed the slowing Zoox vehicle while traveling on northbound [XXX], but then made a mid-block U-turn and rode into the rear of the then-stopped Zoox vehicle in a visibly deliberate manner. The contact resulted in minor scratches on the rear bumper of the Zoox vehicle. The e-scooter rider did not initially indicate that they were injured, and the Zoox operator drove through the intersection to a safe pullover location to assess the damage however, the e-scooter rider later indicated that their "foot hurts". The Police and EMS were then called to the scene, and the e-scooter rider apparently received medical attention and was released. This update provides complete information to date for this incident.

On August [XXX], 2023, Waymo received notice of an allegation that a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV")  contributed to a low-speed collision between a fire engine and an SUV on [XXX] at [XXX].

A Ghost autonomous vehicle was hit by crash debris while traveling on [XXX].  The Ghost vehicle neither hit nor was hit by another vehicle.  The Ghost car was traveling in AV mode with two safety drivers.  Traffic slowed quickly, apparently due to a crash ahead of the Ghost car.  Consistent with their training, the Ghost driver took control of the car by manually braking and disengaging the autonomous system.  The car was traveling 55.3 mph when the driver began to brake.  The Ghost car stopped without impacting the preceding car.  A Mercedes car immediately following the Ghost car also came to a stop without impacting the Ghost car.  Ghost's understanding based on communications at the scene is that a Grand Cherokee traveling behind the Mercedes tried to swerve to avoid impacting the Mercedes but clipped the Mercedes and rolled over.  To Ghost's knowledge, nobody in the Grand Cherokee was injured.  The Ghost drivers heard a noise and then found that the rear bumper of the Ghost car had been damaged, which Ghost believes resulted from crash debris. The Ghost drivers drove the Ghost car back to the garage in conventional mode.

A Zoox vehicle in autonomy was proceeding northbound on [XXX] in stop-and-go traffic through an active construction zone. At the same time, an e-scooter traveling near the right curb was passing other slow traffic behind the Zoox vehicle. Before the e-scooter could also pass the Zoox vehicle on the right, the e-scooter weaved away from the curb, seemingly to avoid a drainage grate, and came within a close following distance behind the Zoox vehicle. The damage to the Zoox vehicle was limited to a cracked tail light lens. This 10-Day update provides complete information for this incident.

On June [XXX], 2022 at approximately 4:50 PM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle (Waymo AV) operating in San Francisco, California allegedly contributed to a collision between a passenger vehicle and a pickup truck on [XXX] at [XXX], according to a claim by the driver of the passenger vehicle.
The Waymo AV was in autonomous mode and preparing to enter southbound [XXX] as a passenger vehicle on [XXX] approached from behind.  A pickup truck was traveling next to the passenger vehicle in the adjacent left lane.  As the passenger vehicle approached the Waymo AV from behind, the passenger vehicle entered the adjacent left lane that was occupied by the pickup truck and maneuvered around the Waymo AV.  The pickup truck proceeded without stopping, and the passenger vehicle's driver shortly after signaled to the Waymo AV test driver to pull over.  The Waymo AV test driver then transitioned to manual mode and pulled over.  Transdev has no data or knowledge of any contact between any of the three vehicles.  There was no contact or collision between the Waymo AV and any other vehicle.  However, the driver and passenger in the passenger vehicle have subsequently alleged injuries based on alleged contact between the pick-up truck and passenger vehicle, which contact their allegations attribute to the behavior of Waymo's AV in a bodily injury claim under Waymo's insurance policy.  Waymo received notice of this insurance claim on July [XXX].
Transdev Alternative Services is reporting this event under Request No. 2 of Standing General Order 2021-01.  Transdev may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.  This report is a duplicate of 30270-3655-1.

On July [XXX], 2022 at 12:57 AM PST a Waymo Autonomous Vehicle ("Waymo AV") was traveling eastbound on [XXX] in autonomous mode when a pedestrian entered the roadway from the center median. The test driver then disengaged autonomous mode and braked to a stop as the pedestrian began to run toward the Waymo AV. The pedestrian stood in front of the vehicle, then jumped onto the hood of the Waymo AV and used their body to break the Waymo AV's windshield. The pedestrian was apprehended soon after by nearby police. The Waymo AV test driver was not physically injured but was taken to a nearby hospital out of an abundance of caution. The Waymo AV sustained major damage to its windshield.
Waymo is reporting this event to ensure official notification to the agency of a notable event. Waymo may supplement or correct its reporting with additional information as it may become available.
